        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 12:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.), instead of “the Father” (1 Ep); and the wish of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "grace and peace",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is followed by the words ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "from God the Father and the Lord Jesus Christ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", wanting in the true text of the former Epistle, but which became from this time a regular part of St Paul’s epistolary greeting. So these great blessings are traced to their source,—twofold yet one: “God the Father” the ultimate spring, “the Lord Jesus Christ” the mediating cause of “grace and peace” to men.",
        "children": []
      },
